          <text>
                    <body>
                              <pb n="1"/>
                              <p rend="align(right)">
                                        <placeName>New York</placeName>
                                        <date>March 30<hi rend="sup">th</hi> 1853</date>
                              </p>
                              <p>
                                        <addressee>Revd Isaac Leeser</addressee>
                              </p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">
                                        <placeName>Philada</placeName>
                              </p>
                              <p rend="indent(2)">My dear Sir</p>
                              <p rend="indent(3)">I have pleasure in again<lb/> waiting on you with
                                        the enclosed Dft. of <persName>Carpenter &amp;
                                                  V<add>?</add></persName><lb/> of the Tradesmans
                                        Bank of your city for One Hundred Dollars<lb/> ($100.—)
                                        which amount please place to my credit against<lb/> balance
                                        due you on my note in your hands</p>
                              <p>In looking over my accounts a few days since I discovered<lb/> that
                                        I had omitted an item of $102.35/100 (remitted you on<lb/>
                                        <date>13<hi rend="sup">th</hi> November 1849</date>.) in the
                                        statement I made for you to <date>Jany/51</date><lb/> the
                                        amt was in <persName>E. P. Massler</persName> Check on
                                        Girard Bank, and<lb/> should have appeared to my credit in
                                        the a/c rendered<lb/> under date of the remittance. Will you
                                        please look into this<lb/> and see if I am not right.</p>
                              <p>I noticed in your last letter what you say about <persName>Mr
                                                  Rox</persName>.<lb/> I am sorry to trouble you
                                        about this matter or to call you from<lb/> your labors, and
                                        would not except for my anxiety to cancel my<lb/> obligation
                                        to you as early as possible.</p>
                              <p>Any one in the neighbourhood of <placeName>2<hi rend="sup">nd</hi>
                                                  and Master Streets<lb/> Kensington</placeName>
                                        will tell you about <persName>John Rox</persName>. as he did
                                        own a<lb/> considerable property about there and was a
                                                  Dyeer<add>?</add> his<lb/> establishment being in
                                                  <placeName>2<hi rend="sup">nd</hi> St.</placeName>
                                        one or two doors above <placeName>master st</placeName></p>
                              <p rend="indent(3)">in haste yours truly <persName role="author"
                                                  ><add>?</add></persName></p>
                              <pb n="2"/>
                              <p>
                                        <addressee>Revd Isaac Leeser</addressee>
                              </p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">
                                        <placeName>Philadelphia</placeName>
                              </p>
